==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*doxtēr'', from Indo-European ''*dʰugh₂ter-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Saxon [[dohtar]] (Dutch [[dochter]]), Old High German [[tochter]] (German [[Tochter]]), Old Franconian [[dohter]], Old Norse [[dóttir]] (Swedish [[dotter]]), Gothic [[𐌳𐌰𐌿𐌷𐍄𐌰𐍂]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Sanskrit [[दुिहतृ]], Avestan ''dugədar-'', Greek [[θυγάτηρ]], Lithuanian [[dukte|duktẽ]], Slavic ''*dъtjī'' (Old Church Slavonic [[дъшти]], Russian [[дочь]]), Tocharian A ''ckācar''.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈdoxtor/}}

===Noun===
'''dohtor''' ''f''
# a [[daughter]]
#:''Ðu scealt cennan sunu and dohtor'': you shall bring forth sons and daughters.

